{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff (filesystem discovery -> filename parsing/sorting -> execution sequencing). A unit test of sort logic alone can miss wiring bugs where discovered files are applied in a different order. Integration is sufficient because this behavior does not require real OS timing, subprocess behavior, network conditions, or AI output. Rejected System: behavior text only requires deterministic ordering by filename prefix, which can be validated with local filesystem fixtures and an in-process executor/DB stub.","test_description":"Create a temp migrations directory with out-of-order files (e.g., 001, 010, 002), run the runner with a test DB/repo layer, and assert execution/recorded application order is 001 -> 002 -> 010.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is idempotency across runs and depends on interaction between migration execution and _migrations metadata persistence/checks. Unit tests on a single function can miss state handoff defects between components. Integration is enough with a local DB/repo fixture. Rejected System: no required real subprocess/OS/network failure mode is stated; the key risk is metadata read/write orchestration.","test_description":"Run the runner once with a migration that changes schema/data, then run it again against the same test DB state. Assert migration body executes only once and _migrations contains a single applied record.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is transaction/error propagation across runner, DB layer, and migration sequencing. Needs real transactional behavior from a local DB-backed integration test; pure unit mocks can hide rollback/stop-on-failure bugs. Rejected System: behavior text does not require subprocess orchestration or external network effects; local DB integration can reproduce rollback and halt semantics.","test_description":"Prepare migration N with multiple statements where one fails, followed by migration N+1. Execute runner against a local test DB and assert: (1) no partial effects from migration N remain, (2) migration N+1 is not attempted, (3) failed migration is not marked applied.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires concurrent starts from separate processes. Real failure boundary is inter-process race/locking/transaction timing, which in-process mocks or single-process integration often hide. Therefore real subprocess execution against the same DB is required.","test_description":"Launch two runner processes simultaneously against the same test PostgreSQL database and shared migrations directory; after both exit, assert each migration effect appears exactly once and _migrations has one record per migration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This checks bootstrap ordering across components (metadata-table initialization and migration execution). A unit test of table-creation helper is too narrow and can miss sequencing bugs in runner orchestration. Integration is sufficient with a fresh local DB state. Rejected System: no real OS/subprocess/network-specific behavior is required beyond normal local DB/module interaction.","test_description":"Start with an empty test DB and at least one migration file; run runner once and assert _migrations exists before first migration is recorded/applied (e.g., via ordered DB observations/log hooks) and run completes successfully.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
